    <!-- Help dialog - Thermic -->
    <string name="help_thermic_title">Thermic forecast help</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_summary">Color shows estimated air updraft in m/s, not glider net climb.</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_model_blocks_info">Colored squares are time-altitude bins; bluer solid colors mean stronger updraft.</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_cursor_info">Cursor details show time, altitude, lift range, top range, confidence, limiter, cloud layer, and model diagnostics.</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_dashed_lines_title">Lines, bands and diagnostics:</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_dry_top_line">Orange hatch - thermal-top uncertainty</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_cloud_base_line">Blue translucent area - possible cloud layer, not dry lift</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_moist_top_line">Purple - moist/cloud top</string>
    <string name="help_thermic_pressure_levels_line">Grey dashed - raw pressure levels</string>

    <!-- Help dialog - Skew-T -->
    <string name="help_stuve_title">Skew-T log-P diagram</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_summary">The Skew-T diagram shows temperature (red) and dewpoint (blue) soundings on a skewed coordinate grid. Tilted isotherms, dry adiabats (green), moist adiabats (dashed teal), and mixing ratio lines (dotted blue) help assess atmospheric stability.</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_tip_1">Where the temperature line is to the right of the parcel path (dashed), the atmosphere is stable; to the left means instability and convection potential.</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_tip_2">The gap between temperature and dewpoint indicates moisture. Where they meet, clouds form (LCL).</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_tip_3">Dots on the sounding lines mark actual model data levels. Use the time slider to view different hours.</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_moisture_strip_info">The pale strip on the right marks layers with elevated relative humidity. It starts around 55% RH; stronger shading means higher RH. It is a moisture cue, not cloud base. Use LCL/CCL for cloud-base estimates.</string>

